Malaria Models

An Overview

October 27, 2023

HUB – Roadmap – Library – Model Building

\(\odot\)

This document – one of the core documents of the RAMP-Model-Library – gives a concise overview of the RAMP framework for model building. This is a conceptual introduction that avoids going into too much technical detail. We take an overview of topics that have been covered in the past 144 years of malaria epidemiology (counting from Laveran), with a focus on how some of the basic features of malaria epidemiology, transmission dynamics, and control have been incorporated into mathematical models. Each one of the topics we introduce here is introduced in much greater depth in other documents – the links that would take you away from this document look like this: (\(\hookrightarrow \boxdot\)). Clicking on this link merely reloads this document. Clicking on that symbol later will open another window with a document describing the concept that precedes it.

Outline

1. Basics – We introduce the framework starting with the Parasite Life-Cycle and the Ross-Macdonald Model, the simplest model you could build that captures the key features of malaria transmission [1]. The framework is designed to be used as part of a state space modeling approach to fit models to data. Working with programs, we need a sound introduction to the basic metrics that are used to measure malaria.

2. Complex Dynamics – This takes deeper dive into blood feeding and parasite transmission, mosquito ecology, malaria epidemiology (in the narrow sense), and human ecology. In these sections, we introduce many of the topics from studies of malaria dynamics and control spanning the past 45 years [2,3].

3. Spatial Dynamics – This section describes how the models can be extended to study parasite dispersal in microsimulation models, and in patch-based models for mosquitoes and adults [4–6]

4. Realism – This tackles a set of issues related to heterogeneity, including exogenous forcing by weather, a large set of issues related to human demographics, and finally stochasticity. We also cover the topic of malaria surveillance.

5. Malaria Control – includes a large set of models for medical interventions and vector control that modify transmission.

6 Evolution covers the evolution of drug and insecticide resistance, the evolution of resistance to diagnostics (e.g. the spread of parasites with HRP2 deletions), and human genetics.

7. Economics covers the burden of malaria, poverty and economic development, …

1- Basics

1.1 Framework

We have developed a comprehensive approach to modeling malaria that does not rely on individual-based simulation [6]. This document introduces malaria epidemiology through a mathematical framework that is modular, flexible, and extensible. The framework has been implemented into two linked software packages: exDE (\(\hookrightarrow \boxdot\)) for solving systems of differential equations describing malaria; and MicroMoB for solving systems of difference equations describing malaria, including stochastic models.

Malaria modeling started with the Ross-Macdonald model, which was developed over a 70 year period after Ross identified parasites in the gut of a mosquito [1]. The simplicity of that model has enormous advantages for teaching basic concepts. At the same time, it has limited applicability for malaria programs, because is missing a lot of features that would be required to manage malaria. After a century, an impressive amount of work has gone into extending the Ross-Macdonald model to address many of those limitations. We have tried to illustrate this in the Figure at the bottom of this page.

Our challenge was to devise a method for building models that are realistic enough and accurate enough to support the needs of malaria programs. Since the needs of malaria programs vary, and since the programs will need to be able to understand the models to participate in the process, and since there is a great deal of uncertainty, we need a framework to build models that can scale complexity and propagate uncertainty. The framework could start with the Ross-Macdonald model, as a way of developing a common understanding and culture within programs that is familiar with the concepts [1]. It will be familiar to some, because is a common starting point for learning about malaria transmission. As we introduce new concepts, we will draw attention to and address its core limitations. We want to introduce a set of algorithms that add realism and complexity so we can build models are realistic enough to suit the needs of a study. We will often need to go several steps beyond the Ross-Macdonald model. When we start adding realism and complexity, we probably won’t know where to stop, so we start with simple and familiar models, and then elaborate until it’s clear we’ve gone too far.

How far could we go? The framework makes it possible to build highly realistic models, including stochastic simulations and individual-based simulations. In model building, we would like to focus on the deterministic backbone of those models, so we can focus on how much detail we are adding to the model, and why. We’ll do as much as we can with probabilistic frameworks first. We want to add complexity and use stochastic models only to serve the needs of a study. To make all this work, the framework must be supported by a rigorous mathematical framework [6], and we will want to test our claims frequently by doing model-model comparison.

The framework has gone to great lengths to ensure that it is possible to add complexity layer upon layer, borrowing one or more of the basic concepts algorithms that developed to study malaria transmission dynamics and control [2,3]. Here, we present fully developed examples using the setup utilities.

Figure: The Framework includes the core concepts of infection dynamics in mosquitoes (\(\cal Y\)) and humans (\(\cal Z\)) linked through blood feeding and transmission. In the framework, blood feeding is a rigorous mathematical concept that links a mosquito activity (searching for blood) to human exposure (through a concept of time at risk) that makes it possible to develop spatial dynamic models [6]. Malaria epidemiology (defined in the narrow sense to include the study of a human disease) is embedded in a model for human ecology, demography, and behavior (\(\cal H\)). Similarly, mosquito dynamics are embedded within a framework for modeling adult (\(\cal M\)) and aquatic (\(\cal L\)) mosquito ecology and population dynamics, with ports and junctions for modeling vector control and exogenous forcing by weather and other factors.

1.2 Life-Cycle

The stages of Plasmodium falciparum as it goes through its life cycle are an important part of the core knowledge for anyone who works in malaria, as are the details that make P. vivax and the other human malaria parasites different. Here, we focus on P. falciparum.

The main features of the life cycle are that it the parasites progress through several live stages.

  • The Bloodmeal: Mosquitoes use vertebrate blood to provision eggs. Adult female mosquitoes search for a vertebrate host. Once they are close, they approach, land, and begin to blood feed. Blood feeding must be understood in its context as a confluence of the activities of humans (and other vertebrate blood hosts) and mosquitoes.

  • Infection – At least two gametocytes – at least one macrogametocye (female) and one microgametocyte (male) – must be present in the bloodmeal for infection to occur. Flagellated microgametocytes must find the macrogametocyte for fertilization to occur. How those gametocytes find each other in the mosquito midgut is another question [7]. After fertilization, the gamete forms, which develops into the zygote. All of this happens in the mosquito gut in a matrix of partially digested blood.

  • The parasites form an ookinete that penetrates the gut of a mosquito and forms an oocyst.

  • After several days, the oocyst ruptures releasing large numbers of sporozoites.

  • The sporozoites migrate into the salivary glands.

  • The Bite: – Sporozoites are transmitted in saliva when a mosquito bites a human before blood feeding.

  • Infection – Some of the sporozoites are sucked back into the mosquito during blood feeding. The remainder must pass through the blood and enter the liver, where they spend about 6 days replicating. Infection herein is defined by parasite replication in a human.

  • The parasites emerge from the liver as merozoites and begin a cycle of replication.

  • Merozoites infect red blood cells, and roughly 48 hours, the red blood cell bursts, releasing merozoites. Initially, parasite densities increase geometrically. They are detectable in blood around the 10th day after the bite, and peak around the 30th day after the bite. What follows is a long decline in parasite densities and a very long duration of infections with parasite densities fluctuating over time.

  • Some of the merozoites are committed to developing into gametocytes. The immature gametocytes sequester in tissues. Mature gametocytes emerge back into circulation after 8-10 day, when they are ready to be taken up in a bloodmeal.

From the point of view of malaria epidemiology and transmission dynamics, some of these details that matter more than others. critical features of this involve the basic features of parasite infections in humans and mosquitoes, including the delays, the duration of infection, infectiousness, and the detectability of parsites.

Figure: There are prettier pictures of the life-cycle of Plasmodium falciparum but this covers the basics.

1.3 Ross-Macdonald

\(\oplus\)

The Ross-Macdonald model does not apply to any particular set of equations [1]. Instead, it’s probably best to think about the Ross-Macdonald model as a few core things:

  • A set of parameters describing malaria transmission by mosquitoes, from Macdonald’s analysis of the sporozoite rate [8];

  • A formula for the basic reproductive number, \(R_0,\) and the associated concept of vectorial capacity [9,10]

  • One of several systems of differential or difference equations describing transmission in which:

    • the host infection dynamics are SIS; the waiting time to clear an infection is exponentially or geometrically distributed;

    • vector dynamics are either SI or SEI, and all parameter values are constant;

    • transmission is mass-action.

  • A set of metrics describing malaria transmission (see 1.4 Metrics)

    • the daily entomological inoculation rate (dEIR);

    • the parasite rate, or prevalence of infection (PR);

    • the force of infection (FoI).

A more technical discussion can be found in a vignette describing the mathematical model (\(\hookrightarrow \boxdot\))

Figure: The Life-Cycle Model

Parameters

In Macdonald’s paper on the sporozoite rate, published in 1952 [8], he names several parameters. Later, these parameters were refined slightly by others. Here, we use the notation from this diagram by Smith, et al. (2014) [3].

  • \(\nu\) is the extrinsic incubation period (EIP)

  • \(m\) is the ratio of mosquitoes to humans; in the model, \(m\) was assumed to be constant. Smith & McKenzie (2004) added an equation \(dm/dt = \lambda - gm,\) so at a steady state \(m=\lambda/g\). The following provides a bit more context:

    • Notably, Macdonald left the math out of the paper, noting that it had been done by his colleague Armitage, who published the math in a terse form in 1953 [11]. In 2004, Smith & McKenzie [12] presented Macdonald’s model for the sporozoite rate with some analysis, including one way of deriving for \(R_0\). [12,13]

    • In 1982, Aron & May [14] presented a slightly revised version of the model with adult population dynamics forced by an emergence rate \(\Lambda\). In the resulting equations, population density was denoted \(M\), and the resulting dynamics were quite simple \[dM/dt = \Lambda - g M.\] If we set \(\Lambda\) to a constant value, let \(M\) come to its steady state, then \(M = \Lambda/g\), and if \(H\) is the human population density, then \(m = M/H\). In the diagram below, we let \(\lambda = \Lambda/H\).

  • \(p\) is the probability of surviving one day

    • the death rate is \(g = -\ln p\), or equivalently, \(p=e^{-g}\), and the average life-expectancy of a mosquito is \(1/g\);

    • the probability of surviving the EIP is \(p^\nu\) or \(e^{-g\nu}\)

  • \(a\) is the human blood feeding rate, but given major differences among species in the propensity to blood feed on humans, we split it into two parameters [15];

    • \(f\) is the overall blood feeding rate;

    • \(q\) is the human fraction;

  • \(b\) is the fraction of bites by infectious mosquitoes that infect a susceptible human;

  • \(c\) is the fraction of blood meals on infectious hosts that infect a mosquito.

  • \(r\) is the clearance rate for human infections;

Dynamics

Macdonald’s version

We can reconstruct the model Macdonald must have used. If we use the parameters we have just defined, and if we let \(x\) denote the prevalence of infected humans, \(y\) the prevalence of infected mosquitoes, and \(z\) the prevalence of infectious mosquitoes; and we let \(x_\tau\) and \(y_\tau\) denote the values of the variables at time \(t-\tau\), then

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \frac{\textstyle{dx}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & mfqbz (1-x) - r x\\ \frac{\textstyle{dy}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fqcx(m-y) - g y\\ \frac{\textstyle{dz}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fqcx_\tau e^{-g\nu} (m - y_\tau) - g z\\ \end{array} \]

In this model, we let \(E\) denote the daily EIR, the product of the human biting rate (\(ma\), HBR) and the sporozoite rate (SR), which we get from solving the equations at the steady state, and:

\[ z \frac{a c x}{g + a c x} e^{-gn}. \]

So

\[\begin{equation} E = maz = \frac{m a^2cx}{g + acx} e^{-gn}. \end{equation}\]

Macdonald’s formula for \(R_0\) and the formula for vectorial capacity (VC, denoted \(V\) in equations) can be derived by considering the EIR as a function of \(\kappa = cx\) and taking a limit of their ratio:

\[\begin{equation} V = \lim_{\kappa \rightarrow 0} ma\frac{z(\kappa)}{\kappa} = m f^2 q^2 \left. \frac{dz(\kappa)}{d\kappa}\right|_{\kappa=0} = \frac{m a^2 }{g} e^{-g\nu} = \lambda \frac{f^2 q^2}{g^2} e^{-g\nu}. \end{equation}\]

An important quantity is \(s=fq/g\), the expected number of human blood meals that a mosquito would take over its lifespan. The right hand side, recapitulated, says that after emergence (\(\lambda\)), a mosquito must bite a human to become infected (\(fq/g\)), then survive the EIP (\(e^{-g\nu}\)), before it becomes infectious and infects humans (\(fq/g\)).

Macdonald’s formula assumes \(c=1\), and it was equivalent to:

\[\begin{equation} R_0 = \frac{bcV}{r}. \end{equation}\]

We can use \(R_0\) as a threshold condition. If \[R_0 >1\] then there is an internal steady state: \[x = \frac{\textstyle{R_0-1}}{\textstyle{R_0 + cs}}\]

In this form, the analysis is elegant, but the model is difficult to explain or extend. We can, however, present a very similar system of differential equations that is

An Extensible Version

If we are to elaborate on the Ross-Macdonald model, adding realism to address policy concerns, as a first step, we need to reformulate the model. When the variables are fractions, it’s difficult to deal with changing denominators. We can, instead, reformulate the model with population densities.

The following system of equations tracks one presented by Aron & May (1982) [14]. We can keep most of the notation, but we let \(H\) denote human population density, \(M\), the adult mosquito population density. We let \(a = fq\):

  • \(X\) is the density of infected and infectious humans;

  • \(Y\) is the density of infected mosquitoes;

  • \(Z\) is the density of infectious mosquitoes;

As before, we let \(X_\tau\) and \(Y_\tau\) denote the values of the variables at time \(t-\tau\).

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \frac{\textstyle{dX}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fqb\frac{\textstyle{Z}}{\textstyle{H}} (H-X) - r X\\ \frac{\textstyle{dY}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fq\frac{\textstyle{c X}}{\textstyle{H}} (M-Y) - g Y\\ \frac{\textstyle{dZ}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fq \frac{\textstyle{c X_\tau}}{\textstyle{H}} e^{-g\nu} (M - Y_\tau) - g Z\\ \end{array} \]

We can get back to Macdonald’s equations with a simple change of variables \(x=X/H\); \(y=Y/M\); and \(z=Z/M\).

1.6 Critique

2 Complexity

-

We extend the Ross-Macdonald model to address major limitations of the models for blood feeding, mosquito ecology, and malaria epidemiology.

Blood Feeding

The first concept we must address is blood feeding. It is the process by which parasites are transmitted, and it is a core non-linearity in models for transmission. Mosquito blood meals are almost certainly not distributed evenly among humans, so heterogeneous exposure is an important factor to consider in any study. Heterogeneous biting modifies the core dynamics and threshold conditions for parasite persistence. Without a rigorous yet flexible model for blood feeding, it would be difficult to extend the Ross-Macdonald model. Here, we examine heterogeneous exposure and heterogeneous transmission in some detail.

Mosquito Ecology

The second topic is mosquito ecology. We start by introducing a basic model for adult mosquito population dynamics after emergence. We will want to consider how weather and vector control can affect mosquito population dynamics, so we introduce models for aquatic ecology that address basic concerns about immature mosquito population development and ecology in aquatic habitats. Since aquatic habitats are structured, we need a way of modeling egg laying by adult mosquitoes. Notably, models that discuss weather, mosquitoes and transmission are handled later, in the section on Realism, and vector control is discussed in depth in Control.

After Macdonald, there was an intense interest in measuring mosquito mortality, which pointed to mosquito parity, and later to mosquito age and senescence. We discuss parity and associated models.

If we want to understand mosquitoes, we need to move beyond the basic assumptions of the Ross-Macdonald model and consider the behavioral states, and the closely related concept of resource availability. We thus introduce behavioral state models.

Finally, we discuss the some of the sticky issues that arise when we want to model malaria transmission when there are multiple vector species present in an area, including competition.

Malaria Epidemiology

By itself, malaria epidemiology (in the narrow sense) is extraordinarily complex. The basic dynamics of the Ross-Macdonald model have been extended in various ways to address several important problems. There are some important concerns about the way the Ross-Macdonald model handles infection, which have been addressed through models for the age of infection (AoI) or stage of infection (SoI), superinfection and the multiplicity of infection (MoI). There are some other important concerns about gametocytes, infectiousness, and transmission. Immunity to malaria develops and modifies almost everything, including disease and its presentation, parasite densities and detection.

Human Behavior & Ecology

Human behavior and ecology play an important role in the dynamics and control of malaria.

2.2 Mosquitoes

2.2.1 Blood Feeding

-

To ensure mathematical consistency in modeling heterogeneous blood feeding and mixing, we need a blood feeding algorithm that has a few key features:

  1. The model of blood feeding should be based on realistic assumptions about mosquito behaviors and physiological constraints;

  2. The number of human bites/bloodmeals taken by mosquitoes over any period should be equal to the number of bites/bloodmeals received by humans over that same period.

  3. It should not be possible for mosquitoes to blood feed if there are no hosts available.

  4. The fraction of bites on humans should be \(0\) if there are no humans, and \(1\) if humans are the only vertebrate hosts available.

  5. Ideally, we would like to be able to modify the model of blood feeding to capture a few key parameters.

Outline

To make the blood feeding model extensible, we introduce a generalized way of modeling heterogeneous biting to understand blood feeding as an interaction between humans (and other blood hosts) and mosquitoes. Here, we are motivated by the analysis of heterogeneous exposure in the PRISM data from Uganda [19], which has been extended to make a key .

  • Threshold conditions when biting his heterogeneous [9,20–25];

  • Reformulating the model for blood feeding around the concepts of biting weights and availability

  • We need to rethink the blood feeding model when the denominators (i.e. availability) changes dynamically. To do so, we introduce the

  • Finally, we introduce the idea of environmental heterogeneity, in which we formulate a new hazard function for heterogeneous exposure.

2.2.2 Heterogeneous Biting
-

Suppose we were in a population where some people got bit by mosquitoes more than others. Many reasons why this could happen have been documented: pregnancy; age; body size; housing quality; living in close proximity to aquatic habitats; elements of breath and sweat that make people more attractive to mosquitoes; spending time outside at dawn or dusk; using repellents or not; using bed nets or not; the number of people in the household. The question for us is how we can understand the effects of heterogeneity on malaria epidemiology, transmission dynamics, and control.

Biting Weights

We start with a simple way of computing and describing relative biting rates, which we will call \(\omega\), assigned to population strata such that the expected dEIR for that stratum is \(\omega E\). We let \(H_\omega\) be the density of humans in a stratum indexed by the relative biting rate. Everyone belongs to some stratum, so:

\[H = \int_0^\infty H_\omega \; d \omega \] Similarly, we can let \(X_\omega\) denote the density of infected humans in each stratum, so
\[X = \int_0^\infty X_\omega \; d \omega \] The prevalence of infection is:

\[ \frac{\textstyle{X}}{\textstyle{H}} = \frac{\textstyle{\int_0^\infty X_\omega d \omega}}{\textstyle{\int_0^\infty H_\omega d \omega}}\]

We want to constrain the distribution such that dEIR is actually the mean. We let \(E\) denote the daily EIR.

\[ \frac{\textstyle{\int_0^\infty \omega E \; H_\omega \; d \omega}}{H} = E\] or

\[ \int_0^\infty \omega \; H_\omega \; d \omega = H\]

We need a practical way of computing \(\omega\) in models, and for this, we adopt a very similar concept called a biting weight, \(v\). We can think of a biting weight as being something like a relative biting rate, but non-normalized. We want to think of the biting weight for a typical member of the population as \(1\), but what counts as typical can change if the composition of the population changes.

  • Biting weights modify the expected dEIR for a stratum;

  • The total biting weight \(v\) is, possibly, the product of biting weights associated with many factors;

  • We let \(H_v = H_\omega\) index the density of the population stratum with total biting weight \(v\). The total availability of hosts is:

\[ \int_0^\infty v \; H_v \; dv\]

  • The relative biting rate is the total biting weight normalized by availability:

\[ \omega = \frac{\textstyle{v}}{\textstyle{\int_0^\infty v \; H_v \; dv}}\]

  • The spatial mixing matrix, \(\beta\) in Spatial Dynamics of Malaria Transmission is computed using biting weights [6].
Dynamics

Heterogeneous biting modifies infection dynamics. To illustrate, we analyze this modified version of the Ross-Macdonald model.

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \frac{\textstyle{dX_\omega}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & b \omega fQ \frac{\textstyle{e^{-g\nu } Y}}{\textstyle{H}} (H_\omega-X_\omega) - r X_\omega\\ \frac{\textstyle{dY}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fQ \frac{\textstyle{c\int_0^\infty \omega X_\omega d\omega}}{\textstyle{H}} (M-Y) - g Y\\ \end{array} \] Add derivation of \(R_0\)

The Ross-Macdonald model computes a threshold condition for parasite persistence. It is based on a concept called the basic reproductive number, \(R_0.\) Malaria transmission can be endemic if \[R_0 > 1.\]

Heterogeneous biting amplifies transmission such that there is a new threshold condition \[R_0(1 + \alpha) > 1,\]

where \(\alpha\) is the coefficient of variation of biting rates.

  • Smith, et al. (2005) [26] explored the dynamics of several models with heterogeneous biting where \(H(\omega)\) was \(\Gamma\)-distributed, for example.

  • Several authors have explored threshold conditions for such models [9,20–25].

2.2.3 Availability

In the Ross-Macdonald model, blood feeding is described by two parameters: an overall blood feeding rate, \(f\), and a human fraction, \(q\). Humans and mosquitoes interactions behave according to the laws of mass-action. These assumptions are a good place to start, but there are some good reasons to develop a framework to model blood feeding when the availability of hosts is changing.

Blood feeding is an activity that involves mosquitoes searching for and attempting to blood feed on a human. We have already introduced the concept of a biting weight. Here, we would like to use it to formulate a generalized model of blood feeding, based on the concept of mosquito searching and the availability of blood hosts. The total availability of humans is:

\[W = \int_0^\infty v H_v \; dv\] We can lump all the other vertebrate blood hosts together into a single term \(O\), and we define the total availability of hosts as:

\[B = W + O^\zeta\]

When \(\zeta=1\), the density of other blood hosts scales linearly with total host availability, but it could scale non-linearly. This simple power law is one (of many) ways of representing this scaling.

More generally, we can let

\[B = W + F_O(O)\]

We want to model blood feeding rates and the human fraction as a function of availability, so we let:

\[f = F_f(B)\]

Where \(F_f\) is any functional form with the constraint that the blood feeding rate must be zero if no hosts are available, \[F_f(0) = 0.\]

\[q = W/B\] Here, we call \(F_f\) the functional response.

2.1.3 Environmental Heterogeneity

In there analysis of CDC light trap mosquito catch counts, heterogeneity was partitioned into a frailty term (e.g. a biting weight), but there was enormous variability that remained [19]. Here, we define environmental heterogeneity to include all of the other sources of variability in exposure to biting mosquitoes. We note that the standard formula relating the dFoI to the dEIR: \(h = b E,\) is consistent with a Poisson distribution. In this model, the daily FoI could be computed for general distribution:

\[ h = F_h(E, b)\] where \(b\) could depend on a model, \(\cal X\), describing infection dynamics. If we let \(b\) have the standard interpretation – the fraction of bites by infectious mosquitoes that would cause an infection in a fully susceptible host – then a negative binomial hazard function with one free parameter, \(\phi\), is:

\[\begin{equation} F_h(E, b, \phi) = \frac{\ln \left(1 + bE \phi \right)} {\phi} \end{equation}\]

Also, see Environmental Heterogeneity.

2.2.1 Adults

GeRM

We want to be able to deal with changing mosquito population densities. The following system of equations tracks one presented by Aron & May (1982) [14]. We let \(\Lambda\) the emergence rate of adult mosquitoes. The variables are:

  • \(M\) is the density of mosquitoes;

  • \(P\) is the density of parous mosquitoes;

  • \(Y\) is the density of infected mosquitoes;

  • \(Z\) is the density of infectious mosquitoes;

As before, we let \(M_\tau\) and \(Y_\tau\) denote the values of the variables at time \(t-\tau\).

\[ \begin{array}{rl} \frac{\textstyle{dM}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & \Lambda - g M \\ \frac{\textstyle{dP}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & f (M-P) - g P\\ \frac{\textstyle{dY}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fq\frac{\textstyle{c X}}{\textstyle{H}} (M-Y) - g Y\\ \frac{\textstyle{dZ}}{\textstyle{dt}} = & fq \frac{\textstyle{c X_\tau}}{\textstyle{H}} e^{-g\nu} (M_\tau - Y_\tau) - g Z\\ \end{array} \]

We can get back to Macdonald’s equations with a simple change of variables: \(y=Y/M\); and \(z=Z/M\).
